Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Alex Y.¶

Introduction¶

Proper Loan Data is to be investigated to find insights for Borrowers and Lenders, it involves an analyis of the Prosper Native Rating System for Borrowers and subsets during the course of the investigation the dataset into finished loan transactions for post-loan analysis.

The dataset comprises of a bit more than 110k observations/rows that collected datapoints for 81 rows if observations where available. While there are several columns which only started to collect data after 2009, these columns and others have a considerable amount of missing values and will mostly not be used, generally though the dataset is very complete and most columns can be investigated.

Main insights can be drawn from both, a lenders and borrowers perspective. For the lender an evaluation of available borrower rating systems can be prioritized, columns that give feedback on borrowers are described in the code cell above: ProsperScore, ProsperRating, and AverageCreditScore. The column CreditGrade will not be considered due to missing datapoints (see Non-Null Count above).

The analysis of the features above will on a first level be conducted by its relation to borrowers ability to uphold their loan agreements, a subset of the dataset that post-loan analyzes loan outcome will be done by the LoanStatus column - categorized into "Completed", "Defaulted", "Chargedoff" loans - and AmountDelinquent column as benchmarks.

Further for estimating a lenders market liquidity and overhead, the average timespan of loans will be be investigated in relation to loan agreement - Term - and others.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Columns that directly affect the transaction from Ratings and Loan Outcome, will be the InterestRate of the Borrower - the dataset subdivided this interest rate into several columns to individually outline "lender-yield" or "paid service-fee", the summation of all Interest towards the borrower side is the column BorrowerAPR will will be mainly used going forward. Further the size of the loans in terms of OriginalAmount will be considered, next the borrowers cashflow and asset-availability through columns like, EmploymentStatus, Occupation, IsHomeOwner, and other will be investigated with a peak look into the borrowers reputation amongs Investors, Recommendations, and InvestmentFromFriendsAmount columns.

Generig Histogram and Countplot Functions for iterative usage¶

In [11]:
def countplot(data, x=None, y=None,hue=None, figsize=(6,4), color=sb.color_palette()[0], x_rotation=0, y_rotation=0):
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sb.countplot(data=data, y=y, x=x, hue=hue, color=color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=x_rotation)
    plt.yticks(rotation=y_rotation);
In [12]:
def hist(data, x=None, figsize=(6,4), color=sb.color_palette()[0], x_rotation=0, y_rotation=0, bins=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    plt.hist(data=data, x=x, color=color, bins=bins)
    plt.xticks(rotation=x_rotation)
    plt.yticks(rotation=y_rotation);

Question 16: Do Borrowers use the full length of their Loan agreement - Term - and how does this differ in differently rated Borrowers?

In [33]:
# timespan of the loan for finished loans
finished_loans['Timespan'] = finished_loans['ClosedDate'] - finished_loans['LoanOriginationDate']
# first convert the timespan to days to later convert to month for comparison in heatmap with agreed term
finished_loans.Timespan = finished_loans.Timespan.dt.days
# Extreme outliers/erros below zero are cut
finished_loans.Timespan = finished_loans.Timespan.mask(finished_loans.Timespan < 0, 0)
# conversion to months by division of average days per month in year (30,437)
finished_loans.Timespan = finished_loans.Timespan/30.437

# Visual of Timespan of finished loans - "finished" is used as definition for post loan analysis to not to confuse transactions
# with "completed" loans that are a subset of "finished" loans, which have been repaid in full in due time
In [34]:
# Heatmap to display multivariate relations of ProsperRating, Term, and Timespan 
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
cat_means = finished_loans.groupby(['Term','ProsperRating (numeric)']).mean()['Timespan']
cat_means = cat_means.reset_index(name='Mean Timespan in months')
cat_means = cat_means.pivot(index = 'ProsperRating (numeric)', values= 'Mean Timespan in months', columns='Term')

sb.heatmap(cat_means, annot = True, fmt = '.1f',
          cbar_kws = {'label' : 'Mean Timespan Of Finished Loan Transactions In Months'});

Observation: After having evaluated Prosper Score and Prosper Rating as effective benchmarks earlier, for estimating the creditors/lenders needed of working capital/liquidity, a subset of the dataframe that only considers finished loans - completed, defaulted, or chargedoff - was investigated that compared the actual times of the loan with the Term (length of agreed loan contract) in relation to the Prosper Rating.

It was found that overall the lifespan of a loan is significanlty shorter than the term, suggesting, that in partial cases subsequent MonthlyLoanPayments are delinquent, leading to early Chargeoff or Defaulted status, while on the contrary Loans are Completed ahead of time, likely for the borrowers to save high Interest Rates. Latter is concluded from the fact that mid-, and longer term loans (36-60 months) are paid earlier, the higher the Prosper Rating (highest is 1 > lowest is 7) . On the contrary short term loans are finished signficantly faster by lower rated borrowers, it is presumed that these short term loans for low-rated borrowers, are of of the highest APR.

Conclusions¶

The key findings are that the Prosper Rating and Score are fairly accurate for lenders to predict loan outcome an and therefore risk and profit margins.This rating system does not align with the rating of the Consumer Credit Agency, which needed to be evaluated differently. A major underlying causality for these outcomes however are the higher Interest rates for lower rated Borrowers. Further, the final observation that showed that loans are finished in most cases prior to the end of the term of the loan agreement allow a more efficient capital allocation for lenders.
